</mxCell> <mxCell id="Ei2sgQtYdHAILAkHYD0M-47" value="<div style="text-align: justify"><h3 style="font-family: Times; text-align: start;">The Road to Enlightenment</h3><p style="font-family: Times; font-size: medium; text-align: start;">Littering a dark and dreary road lay the past relics of browser-specific tags, incompatible&nbsp;<abbr title="Document Object Model">DOM</abbr>s, broken&nbsp;<abbr title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>&nbsp;support, and abandoned browsers.</p><p style="font-family: Times; font-size: medium; text-align: start;">We must clear the mind of the past. Web enlightenment has been achieved thanks to the tireless efforts of folk like the&nbsp;<abbr title="World Wide Web Consortium">W3C</abbr>,&nbsp;<abbr title="Web Standards Project">WaSP</abbr>, and the major browser creators.</p><p style="font-family: Times; font-size: medium; text-align: start;">The CSS Zen Garden invites you to relax and meditate on the important lessons of the masters. Begin to see with clarity. Learn to use the time-honored techniques in new and invigorating fashion. Become one with the web.</p></div>" style="whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;rounded=0;shadow=0;labelBackgroundColor=none;strokeWidth=1;fillColor=none;fontFamily=Verdana;fontSize=12;align=center;verticalAlign=top;spacing=10;comic=1;" vertex="1" parent="1"> <mxGeometry x="570" y="684" width="475" height="316" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="Ei2sgQtYdHAILAkHYD0M-48" value="<div style="text-align: justify"><h3><font style="font-size: 11px;">So What is This About?</font></h3><h3 style="text-align: start;"><div style="font-weight: 400;" role="article" id="zen-explanation" class="explanation"><p style="font-family: Times;"><font style="font-size: 11px;">There is a continuing need to show the power of&nbsp;<abbr style="" title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>. The Zen Garden aims to excite, inspire, and encourage participation. To begin, view some of the existing designs in the list. Clicking on any one will load the style sheet into this very page. The&nbsp;<abbr style="" title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr>&nbsp;remains the same, the only thing that has changed is the external&nbsp;<abbr style="" title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>&nbsp;file. Yes, really.</font></p><p style=""><font face="Times New Roman" style="font-size: 11px;"><abbr style="" title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>&nbsp;allows complete and total control over the style of a hypertext document. The only way this can be illustrated in a way that gets people excited is by demonstrating what it can truly be, once the reins are placed in the hands of those able to create beauty from structure. Designers and coders alike have contributed to the beauty of the web; we can always push it further.</font></p><div style="font-family: Times;"><br></div></div><div style="font-family: Times; font-size: medium; font-weight: 400;" role="article" id="zen-participation" class="participation"></div></h3></div>" style="whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;rounded=0;shadow=0;labelBackgroundColor=none;strokeWidth=1;fillColor=none;fontFamily=Verdana;fontSize=12;align=center;verticalAlign=top;spacing=10;comic=1;" vertex="1" parent="1"> <mxGeometry x="30" y="1030" width="360" height="280" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="Ei2sgQtYdHAILAkHYD0M-50" value="<div style="text-align: justify"><h3 style="text-align: start;"><font style="font-size: 11px;">Participation</font></h3><h3><p style="font-family: Times; font-weight: 400; text-align: start;"><font style="font-size: 11px;">Strong visual design has always been our focus. You are modifying this page, so strong&nbsp;<abbr style="" title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>&nbsp;skills are necessary too, but the example files are commented well enough that even&nbsp;<abbr style="" title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>&nbsp;novices can use them as starting points. Please see the&nbsp;<a style="" title="A listing of CSS-related resources" href="/pages/resources/"><abbr title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>&nbsp;Resource Guide</a>&nbsp;for advanced tutorials and tips on working with&nbsp;<abbr style="" title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>.</font></p><p style="font-family: Times; font-weight: 400; text-align: start;"><font style="font-size: 11px;">You may modify the style sheet in any way you wish, but not the&nbsp;<abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr>. This may seem daunting at first if you’ve never worked this way before, but follow the listed links to learn more, and use the sample files as a guide.</font></p><p style="font-family: Times; font-weight: 400; text-align: start;"><font style="font-size: 11px;">Download the sample&nbsp;<a style="" title="This page's source HTML code, not to be modified." href="/examples/index">HTML</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a style="" title="This page's sample CSS, the file you may modify." href="/examples/style.css">CSS</a>&nbsp;to work on a copy locally. The CSS Zen Garden is about functional, practical&nbsp;<abbr title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>&nbsp;and not the latest bleeding-edge tricks viewable by 2% of the browsing public. The only real requirement we have is that your&nbsp;<abbr title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>&nbsp;validates.</font></p><p style="font-weight: 400;"><font style="font-size: 10px;">Luckily, designing this way shows how well various browsers have implemented&nbsp;<abbr title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>&nbsp;by now. When sticking to the guidelines you should see fairly consistent results across most modern browsers. Due to the sheer number of user agents on the web these days — especially when you factor in mobile — pixel-perfect layouts may not be possible across every platform. That’s okay, but do test in as many as you can. Your design should work in at least IE9+ and the latest Chrome, Firefox, iOS and Android browsers (run by over 90% of the population).</font></p><p style="font-weight: 400;"><font style="font-size: 10px;">We ask that you submit original artwork. Please respect copyright laws. Please keep objectionable material to a minimum, and try to incorporate unique and interesting visual themes to your work. We’re well past the point of needing another garden-related design.</font></p><p style="font-weight: 400;"><font style="font-size: 10px;">This is a learning exercise as well as a demonstration. div.p: Littering a dark and dreary road lay the past relics of browser-specific tags, incompatible DOMs, broken CSS support, and abandoned browsers.

p.style: font-family: Times; font-size: medium; text-align: start;

div.p: We must clear the mind of the past. Web enlightenment has been achieved thanks to the tireless efforts of folk like the W3C, WaSP, and the major browser creators.

p.style: font-family: Times; font-size: medium; text-align: start;

div.p: The CSS Zen Garden invites you to relax and meditate on the important lessons of the masters. Begin to see with clarity. Learn to use the time-honored techniques in new and invigorating fashion. Become one with the web.

p.font: There is a continuing need to show the power of CSS. The Zen Garden aims to excite, inspire, and encourage participation. To begin, view some of the existing designs in the list. Clicking on any one will load the style sheet into this very page. The HTML remains the same, the only thing that has changed is the external CSS file. Yes, really.

CSS allows complete and total control over the style of a hypertext document. The only way this can be illustrated in a way that gets people excited is by demonstrating what it can truly be, once the reins are placed in the hands of those able to create beauty from structure. Designers and coders alike have contributed to the beauty of the web; we can always push it further.

p.font: Strong visual design has always been our focus. You are modifying this page, so strong CSS skills are necessary too, but the example files are commented well enough that even CSS novices can use them as starting points. Please see the CSS Resource Guide for advanced tutorials and tips on working with CSS.

You may modify the style sheet in any way you wish, but not the HTML. This may seem daunting at first if you’ve never worked this way before, but follow the listed links to learn more, and use the sample files as a guide.

Download the sample HTML and CSS to work on a copy locally. Once you have completed your masterpiece (and please, don’t submit half-finished work) upload your CSS file to a web server under your control. Send us a link to an archive of that file and all associated assets, and if we choose to use it we will download it and place it on

h3.p: Why participate? For recognition, inspiration, and a resource we can all refer to showing people how amazing CSS really can be. This site serves as equal parts inspiration for those working on the web today, learning tool for those who will be tomorrow, and gallery of future techniques we can all look forward to.

p.font: Where possible, we would like to see mostly CSS 1 & 2 usage. CSS 3 & 4 should be limited to widely-supported elements only, or strong fallbacks should be provided. The CSS Zen Garden is about functional, practical CSS and not the latest bleeding-edge tricks viewable by 2% of the browsing public. The only real requirement we have is that your CSS validates.

Luckily, designing this way shows how well various browsers have implemented CSS by now. When sticking to the guidelines you should see fairly consistent results across most modern browsers. Due to the sheer number of user agents on the web these days — especially when you factor in mobile — pixel-perfect layouts may not be possible across every platform. That’s okay, but do test in as many as you can. Your design should work in at least IE9+ and the latest Chrome, Firefox, iOS and Android browsers (run by over 90% of the population).

We ask that you submit original artwork. Please respect copyright laws. Please keep objectionable material to a minimum, and try to incorporate unique and interesting visual themes to your work. We’re well past the point of needing another garden-related design.

This is a learning exercise as well as a demonstration. You retain full copyright on your graphics (with limited exceptions, see submission guidelines), but we ask you release your CSS under a Creative Commons license identical to the one on this site so that others may learn from your work.
